> screen -t &quot;foo&quot;<p>You mean<p><pre><code>    screen -S &quot;foo&quot;
</code></pre>
right?

In C++, << has higher precedence than &&, so in effect what is being done is<p><pre><code>    (cout << 1) && 2;
</code></pre>
...which is not an error, since the result of operator<< is an std::ostream, which is convertible to bool. Therefore operator&&(bool, bool) is invoked but the result is, of course, discarded.<p>Disambiguating the expression with parentheses should output 1 in every case.
